VALUES
(18, 5, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'and envy slayeth the silly one.', 35, 66, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Envy''', 'ζηλοτυπία (zelotupia, G2206) - envy, jealousy. This term captures the intense desire for what others possess, which often leads to destructive behavior. Understanding this word enriches our comprehension of the emotional and spiritual ramifications of envy as described in this verse.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2206", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term for envy."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'I have seen the foolish taking root: but suddenly I cursed his habitation.', 0, 74, 'connection', 'Foolishness and Consequences', 'This verse resonates with Psalm 37:35-36, where the psalmist describes the prosperity of the wicked and their sudden downfall. Both passages emphasize the transient nature of the wicked’s success and the certainty of divine judgment. Understanding this connection highlights the theme of divine justice that runs throughout Scripture, illustrating that apparent stability for the foolish is often deceptive.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 37:35-36", "description": "Describes the fleeting success of the wicked."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'I have seen the foolish taking root: but suddenly I cursed his habitation.', 0, 74, 'theology', 'Divine Justice', 'This passage suggests that God''s justice is both certain and swift. Many scholars believe that the phrase ''suddenly I cursed'' reflects the immediacy of God''s response to unrighteousness. This highlights a key theological principle: God is active in human affairs, ensuring that evil does not prevail indefinitely. Understanding this can encourage believers to trust in God''s timing and justice.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'I have seen the foolish taking root: but suddenly I cursed his habitation.', 0, 74, 'question', 'Reflection on Foolishness', 'What does it mean for someone to ''take root'' in foolishness, and how might this apply to areas of our lives where we may be compromising our values? Reflecting on this can help us identify where we might be building our lives on unstable foundations.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'I have seen the foolish taking root: but suddenly I cursed his habitation.', 0, 74, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Cursed''', 'מְקַלֵּל (meqallel, H7043) - to curse, to invoke evil upon. This term signifies not just a spoken curse, but an active declaration of God''s judgment. The weight of this word illustrates the severity and intentionality behind God''s response to the foolish.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7043", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word meaning ''to curse''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'His children are far from safety', 0, 32, 'connection', 'Children''s Vulnerability', 'This phrase resonates with Psalm 127:4-5, which states that children are a heritage from the Lord and blessed is the man whose quiver is full of them. The contrast here highlights the tragic reality that the children of the foolish are not only unprotected but also suffer dire consequences. It underscores the importance of wise living for the sake of one''s descendants.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 127:4-5", "description": "Highlights the value of children as blessings"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'they are crushed in the gate', 38, 66, 'theology', 'Symbolism of the Gate', 'The ''gate'' often symbolizes a place of judgment and authority in biblical texts. Many scholars believe that being ''crushed in the gate'' indicates not only physical oppression but also spiritual and social failure. This reflects the consequences of a society that neglects justice and righteousness, leading to the suffering of the innocent.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the implications of societal justice"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'neither is there any to deliver them', 68, 104, 'question', 'Deliverance Reflection', 'What does this absence of deliverance reveal about the nature of community and responsibility? How does it challenge our understanding of our role in advocating for those who are vulnerable and oppressed? This prompts reflection on our duty to act as agents of deliverance in our own contexts.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'Whose harvest the hungry eateth up, and taketh it even out of the thorns, and the robber swalloweth up their substance.', 0, 119, 'connection', 'God''s Justice in Affliction', 'This verse connects with Matthew 7:16, where it is stated, ''You will know them by their fruits.'' The imagery of the hungry consuming the harvest highlights the consequences of injustice, resonating with Jesus'' teachings about the outcomes of one’s actions. It emphasizes that those who exploit others will ultimately face divine justice. This connection matters as it reinforces the theme of moral accountability present throughout Scripture.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 7:16", "description": "Jesus teaches about recognizing true character through actions."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'Whose harvest the hungry eateth up, and taketh it even out of the thorns, and the robber swalloweth up their substance.', 0, 119, 'theology', 'The Reality of Human Suffering', 'Many scholars believe this verse reflects the pervasive nature of human suffering and injustice. It suggests that the innocent often suffer at the hands of the wicked, a theme echoed throughout the book of Job. This understanding aids in grappling with theodicy—why a good God permits evil. It encourages believers to seek justice and mercy in their actions, reflecting God''s character in a broken world.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Job Commentary by John Gill", "description": "Explores themes of justice and suffering in the book of Job."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'Whose harvest the hungry eateth up, and taketh it even out of the thorns, and the robber swalloweth up their substance.', 0, 119, 'question', 'Reflection on Justice', 'In what ways do we see the hungry and the oppressed in our own lives today? How can we actively participate in bringing justice and support to those who suffer as described in this verse? Reflecting on these questions encourages a deeper understanding of our role in confronting injustice.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'and taketh it even out of the thorns', 36, 72, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Thorns''', 'ἀκάνθαις (akanthais, G173) - thorns, prickly plants. This term underscores the harshness of the environment from which the hungry are taking sustenance. Thorns symbolize obstacles and suffering, suggesting that even in dire circumstances, survival is possible, though fraught with difficulty.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G173", "description": "Strong''s number for ''thorns'' in the New Testament."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'Although affliction cometh not forth of the dust', 0, 48, 'theology', 'Nature of Affliction', 'This phrase suggests that suffering does not arise from nothingness but has causes rooted in the fallen state of the world. Many scholars believe this reflects the Biblical teaching on the nature of sin and its consequences, as outlined in Genesis 3:16-19, where the fall introduces toil and pain into human experience. Understanding this concept can help believers grasp the relational dynamics between humanity and God amidst suffering.', 'figure.mind.and.body', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 3:16-19", "description": "Explains the origins of suffering and toil in the fallen world."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'neither doth trouble spring out of the ground', 50, 95, 'connection', 'Source of Troubles', 'This phrase connects with Psalm 90:10, which speaks about the brevity of life and the troubles that often accompany it. The connection emphasizes that troubles are not natural or inherent to creation but are a result of the human condition and sin. Understanding this can help believers recognize the need for divine intervention in their struggles.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 90:10", "description": "Highlights the transient nature of life and the accompanying troubles."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'affliction cometh not forth of the dust', 9, 48, 'greek', 'Significance of ''Affliction''', 'Although the verse is in Hebrew, the concept of affliction parallels the Greek term ''θλῖψις'' (thlipsis, G2347), meaning pressure or tribulation. This term emphasizes the weight and burden of suffering, revealing that trials are not trivial but deeply impactful. Understanding the root of affliction can guide believers in approaching their own trials with a perspective rooted in faith.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2347", "description": "Indicates the nature of trials and tribulations."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'trouble spring out of the ground', 63, 95, 'question', 'Understanding Trouble''s Origins', 'What does it imply that trouble does not spring from the ground, and how does this shape our understanding of the sources of our struggles? Reflecting on this can lead to deeper insights about the spiritual versus physical origins of our trials and encourage seeking God''s perspective in times of distress.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'Yet man is born unto trouble, as the sparks fly upward.', 0, 55, 'connection', 'Human Struggle in Scripture', 'This verse echoes the sentiment found in Psalm 90:10, which states that our days are filled with trouble and sorrow. Both passages highlight the inevitability of suffering in human life, reinforcing that trouble is a common experience across generations. Understanding this connection helps to frame the broader context of human existence in relation to divine providence.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 90:10", "description": "A reminder of the fleeting nature of life and the struggles that accompany it."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'as the sparks fly upward.', 30, 55, 'theology', 'Nature of Human Existence', 'Many scholars believe that this imagery of sparks flying upward symbolizes the inherent nature of human suffering as part of the created order. It suggests that just as sparks naturally ascend, so too is trouble an inevitable aspect of the human condition. This aligns with the theological understanding that suffering can lead to spiritual growth and reliance on God.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'man is born unto trouble', 4, 28, 'question', 'Reflection on Suffering', 'What does it mean for you to acknowledge that ''man is born unto trouble''? How can this perspective influence your understanding of God’s presence in times of hardship?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'Yet man is born unto trouble', 0, 28, 'greek', 'Understanding ''born''', 'יָּלַד (yalad, H3205) - to bear, bring forth, or beget. This term emphasizes the idea of being born into a condition rather than merely experiencing it. It suggests a deep-rooted aspect of human existence that is intertwined with suffering from the very beginning.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3205", "description": "Strong''s number for understanding the Hebrew term for ''born''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'I would seek unto God, and unto God would I commit my cause:', 0, 60, 'connection', 'Seeking God’s Guidance', 'This verse resonates with Psalm 55:22, which encourages casting burdens on the Lord, and 1 Peter 5:7, where believers are urged to cast all anxieties on Him. The connection highlights a biblical pattern of seeking God in times of trouble, reinforcing the idea that divine assistance is foundational for resolving life’s challenges.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 55:22", "description": "Encourages believers to cast their burdens on the Lord."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Peter 5:7", "description": "Urges believers to bring their anxieties to God."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'I would seek unto God, and unto God would I commit my cause:', 0, 60, 'theology', 'Commitment to God', 'This verse suggests a deep theological principle of reliance on God for justice and support. Many scholars believe that committing one''s cause to God reflects the concept of divine sovereignty, where believers acknowledge God''s ultimate authority over their circumstances. This aligns with the broader Christian teaching of faith in God''s providence.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'I would seek unto God, and unto God would I commit my cause:', 0, 60, 'question', 'Personal Commitment Reflection', 'What does it mean to truly ''commit my cause'' to God in the context of your own struggles? How can you incorporate seeking God actively into your daily decisions and challenges?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'I would seek unto God, and unto God would I commit my cause:', 0, 60, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Seek''', 'בָּקַשׁ (baqash, H1245) - to seek, inquire, or request. This term emphasizes an active pursuit of God, indicating not just a passive waiting but a diligent search for divine intervention and wisdom.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1245", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word used in seeking."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'Which doeth great things and unsearchable; marvellous things without number:', 0, 76, 'connection', 'God''s Unsearchable Works', 'This phrase resonates with Psalm 145:3, which states, ''Great is the Lord, and greatly to be praised; and his greatness is unsearchable.'' Both verses emphasize the vastness of God''s works and wisdom. This connection highlights the theme of divine mystery and the awe-inspiring nature of God''s actions in creation and human experience.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 145:3", "description": "Emphasizes the greatness of God."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'Which doeth great things and unsearchable;', 0, 42, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Unsearchable''', 'ἀνεξιχνίαστος (anexichniastos, G421) - unsearchable, inscrutable. This term conveys the idea that God''s ways and works are beyond human comprehension. The use of this word invites believers to recognize their limitations in understanding God''s plans and encourages trust in His wisdom.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G421", "description": "Strong''s number for ''unsearchable''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'marvellous things without number:', 43, 76, 'theology', 'God''s Marvelous Works', 'Many scholars believe that the phrase ''marvellous things without number'' reflects God''s limitless capacity to perform wonders. In Christian theology, this underscores God''s sovereignty and omnipotence, suggesting that His acts are not only beyond human ability to quantify but also demonstrate His grace and love towards creation.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses God''s marvelous works."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'Which doeth great things and unsearchable;', 0, 42, 'question', 'Reflecting on God''s Works', 'What does it mean to you that God does ''great things and unsearchable''? How does this understanding influence your trust in His plan during difficult times?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'giveth rain upon the earth', 4, 30, 'connection', 'Divine Provision', 'This phrase connects to Psalm 147:8, which states, ''He covers the heavens with clouds; He prepares rain for the earth.'' Both verses highlight God''s role as the provider of natural resources essential for life. Recognizing God as the source of rain emphasizes His sovereignty over creation and His ongoing care for humanity.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 147:8", "description": "Highlights God''s provision through nature."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'sendeth waters upon the fields', 36, 66, 'theology', 'God''s Nurturing Care', 'This passage suggests that God’s provision is not just for survival but also for flourishing. Many scholars believe that the imagery of God sending waters signifies His nurturing aspect, wherein He sustains and enables growth in creation. This aligns with the broader biblical theme of God caring for His creation, as seen in Matthew 6:26 where He cares for the birds of the air.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'Who giveth rain upon the earth', 0, 30, 'greek', 'Hebrew Insight', 'מָטָר (matar, H4306) - rain. This word signifies not just precipitation but also the blessings that rain brings, such as fertility and abundance. In the ancient Near Eastern context, rain was vital for agriculture, making this term rich in cultural and spiritual significance.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4306", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term for rain."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'sendeth waters upon the fields', 36, 66, 'question', 'Reflecting on God''s Provision', 'How does understanding God as the one who sends rain and waters shape your view of His provision in your life? In what ways can you recognize His blessings, both physically and spiritually, as He nurtures your growth?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'To set up on high those that be low;', 0, 36, 'connection', 'Exaltation of the Humble', 'This phrase resonates with Luke 1:52, where Mary proclaims, ''He hath put down the mighty from their seats, and exalted them of low degree.'' Both verses emphasize God''s sovereign action in lifting up the humble and lowly. This connection highlights a recurring biblical theme of divine reversal, where societal standards are upended by God''s justice and mercy.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Luke 1:52", "description": "Mary''s Magnificat reflects the same theme of God exalting the humble."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'that those which mourn may be exalted to safety.', 37, 85, 'theology', 'Comfort for the Mourning', 'This passage suggests that God offers comfort and exaltation to those who mourn, reinforcing the biblical teaching found in Matthew 5:4, ''Blessed are they that mourn: for they shall be comforted.'' Many scholars believe this reflects God''s care for the brokenhearted, emphasizing the hope found in divine consolation and safety for those enduring suffering.', 'figure.mind.and.body', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 5:4", "description": "Jesus teaches about the blessing of mourning and the promise of comfort."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'those that be low;', 18, 36, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Low''', 'שָׁפָל (shaphal, H8213) - to be low, to be humbled. This Hebrew term indicates a state of lowliness or humility, reflecting the condition of those who are oppressed or marginalized. Understanding this term deepens the reader''s appreciation of God''s promise to elevate the downtrodden.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8213", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word meaning ''to be low.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'that those which mourn may be exalted to safety.', 37, 85, 'question', 'Reflection on Mourning', 'What does it mean to you that God promises to exalt those who mourn? In what ways can you experience or share this comfort within your community?', 'heart.text.square', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'He disappointeth the devices of the crafty', 0, 42, 'connection', 'Craftiness vs. Divine Wisdom', 'This phrase connects with 1 Corinthians 3:19, which states, ''For the wisdom of this world is foolishness with God.'' Both verses emphasize how God thwarts human cunning and schemes. Understanding this connection helps illuminate the theme of divine sovereignty over human intellect and plans, reinforcing that true wisdom comes from God alone.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Corinthians 3:19", "description": "This verse highlights God''s superiority over worldly wisdom."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'so that their hands cannot perform their enterprise', 44, 95, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty in Action', 'This passage suggests that God''s sovereignty extends to thwarting the plans of the wicked. Many scholars believe that this reflects the broader biblical theme where God actively intervenes in history to protect His purposes. This understanding can shape our view of justice, reminding us that no human scheme can ultimately succeed against God''s will.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'He disappointeth the devices of the crafty', 0, 42, 'question', 'Reflection on Human Plans', 'In what ways do I rely on my own cleverness or craftiness instead of trusting in God''s plans? How might this verse encourage me to align my intentions with God''s wisdom?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'devices of the crafty', 21, 42, 'greek', 'Understanding ''devices''', 'מַזִּימֹות (mazzimot, H4219) - devices, plans, schemes. This Hebrew term indicates the intricate and often deceptive plans devised by individuals. Understanding this word enhances our comprehension of the crafty nature of human schemes that stand in contrast to God''s omniscience.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4219", "description": "The Hebrew word for devices indicating plans."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'He taketh the wise in their own craftiness', 0, 42, 'connection', 'Wisdom in Foolishness', 'This phrase connects closely with 1 Corinthians 3:19, which states, ''For the wisdom of this world is foolishness with God.'' It highlights God''s sovereignty over human wisdom and the futility of relying on one''s own understanding. This connection emphasizes that true wisdom comes from God, and those who depend solely on their own intellect may ultimately find themselves ensnared by their own schemes.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Corinthians 3:19", "description": "Paul''s teaching on worldly wisdom versus divine wisdom"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'and the counsel of the froward is carried headlong.', 44, 95, 'theology', 'Divine Justice and Judgment', 'Many scholars believe this verse reflects a key aspect of divine justice: that God actively thwarts the plans of the wicked. The term ''froward'' suggests a willful perversion of right. This aligns with the biblical theme that God will not allow injustice to prevail and will ultimately frustrate the schemes of those who oppose His will. This reinforces the idea that God''s righteousness prevails over human deceit.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary on the Whole Bible", "description": "Discussion on God''s judgment against the wicked"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'He taketh the wise in their own craftiness', 0, 42, 'question', 'Reflection on Wisdom', 'What does it reveal about human nature that we often rely on our own craftiness instead of seeking God''s wisdom? How can acknowledging our limitations lead us to a deeper dependence on God''s guidance in our lives?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'They meet with darkness in the daytime, and grope in the noonday as in the night.', 0, 81, 'connection', 'Spiritual Blindness', 'This verse resonates with John 12:35, where Jesus speaks of walking in the light to avoid darkness. Both passages highlight the theme of spiritual blindness and the dire consequences of ignoring divine illumination. In Job, the ''darkness'' symbolizes the despair and confusion faced by the wicked, while in John, it serves as a warning to those who reject the light of Christ.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "John 12:35", "description": "Jesus emphasizes the importance of walking in the light."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'darkness in the daytime', 15, 38, 'theology', 'The Nature of Suffering', 'This phrase suggests that even in seemingly bright times, individuals can experience profound darkness. Many scholars believe this reflects the paradox of the human condition where suffering can occur amidst prosperity. It aligns with the theological concept that God allows trials to refine faith and reveal the true state of the heart.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the role of suffering in spiritual growth."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'grope in the noonday as in the night', 44, 80, 'question', 'Understanding Spiritual Groping', 'What does it mean to ''grope'' in the light of day, and how does this metaphor reflect our own spiritual struggles? Consider how often we rely on our own understanding rather than seeking divine guidance, leading to confusion even when we should have clarity. How can we ensure we are truly walking in the light?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'darkness in the daytime', 15, 38, 'greek', 'Hebrew Word Study', 'חֹשֶׁךְ (choshekh, H2822) - darkness, obscurity. This term often symbolizes not just physical darkness but spiritual ignorance and moral failure. Its use here emphasizes the severity of the situation, indicating a deep inability to perceive truth even when it is present.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2822", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term for darkness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'he saveth the poor', 4, 22, 'connection', 'Divine Deliverance Theme', 'This phrase resonates with Psalms 34:6, which states, ''This poor man cried, and the Lord heard him, and saved him out of all his troubles.'' Both verses emphasize God''s attentive care for the marginalized and His role as a savior. This connection underscores the consistent biblical theme that God actively protects and saves the vulnerable, reinforcing the idea of divine justice.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalms 34:6", "description": "Highlights God''s deliverance of the poor."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'from the sword, from their mouth, and from the hand of the mighty', 23, 88, 'theology', 'God''s Protection Mechanisms', 'This passage suggests that God''s protection encompasses various forms of threat—physical violence, harmful speech, and oppressive power. Many scholars believe this illustrates the comprehensive nature of divine salvation, affirming that God not only saves from physical dangers but also from verbal and systemic oppression. This reflects God''s holistic concern for justice and mercy.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(18, 5, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'he saveth the poor', 4, 22, 'greek', 'Hebrew Understanding of Salvation', 'יָשַׁע (yasha, H3467) - to save, deliver, or rescue. This Hebrew word conveys a sense of active intervention by God on behalf of those in distress. The use of this term in Job 5:15 indicates that God''s salvation is not merely spiritual but also practical, addressing immediate needs and dangers faced by the poor.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3467", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for salvation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');